We iterate over `i` from `n-1` to 0, and for each `i`, we iterate over `j` from `k` to 0. For each `(i, j)` pair, we update `dp[i+1]` to be the minimum of `dp[i+1]` and `dp[i] + 1`. This represents the minimum number of digits needed to form a password starting from position `i` and considering position `j`.

Finally, we return the value stored at `dp[k]`, which represents the minimum number of digits needed to form a password starting from the last digit position (k-th digit).

This solution has a time complexity of O(n * k) because we iterate over `i` and `j` for each valid combination of `i` and `j`. The space complexity is O(k) because we only use a single array `dp` of size `k+1`. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only requires a constant amount of energy to perform the calculations.

